          "body": "The chapter's theological center of gravity is 12:17-18. David's interrogation of the arriving Benjaminite and Judahite warriors is a rare window into his interior life: 'my heart shall be united with you; but if to betray me to my adversaries… may the God of our fathers look on it and decide.' David does not have the political power to coerce or punish betrayers — he appeals to divine justice. Then the Spirit 'clothed' (*lavash*) Amasai, and Amasai spoke an oracle: 'We are yours, O David… your God helps you.' The verb *lavash* — literally to put on as a garment — is used elsewhere of the Spirit's clothing of Gideon (Judg 6:34) and Zechariah (2 Chron 24:20). It is the language of prophetic empowerment. What this means theologically is decisive: the human gathering of chapter 12 is not merely political loyalty; it is the Spirit-authenticated alignment of Israel with the king God has chosen. To come to David is to align with God. The oracle makes the implicit explicit."
